<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-261-854  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 261 854.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  March 12 1990 v4 n10 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Factors in choosing an optical storage technology.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>O'Dell, Jim L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The selection and acquisition of an optical storage technologyrequires consideration of several technical issues and planning togain management approval.andP;  There are now several opticaltechnologies available: write-once/read-many (WORM), optical tape,and erasable or rewritable optical drives.andP;  Technical aspects ofeach optical media should be reviewed in light of the targetapplication.andP;  These issues include access time versus estimatedaccess frequency, the permanence of the data storage format versushow long data will be retained, and the security of thetechnology.andP;  Planning to obtain management approval for acquiringthe selected technology requires showing how the opticaltechnology will support the organization's goals and demonstratingthe economic benefits.andP;  The latter process could demonstrateproductivity improvements, space savings, and staff reductions.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TutorialHardware SelectionCriteriaOptical MemoryWORMCost Benefit Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>